{"title_page": "Hillcrest High School, Hamilton", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=April 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2018}}\n{{advert|date=April 2013}}\n{{Infobox school\n| name        = Hillcrest High School\n| seal_image  = Hhsbadge.png\n| motto       = Circumspice \n| motto_translation= Look Around You\n| fundingtype = State\n| gender      = Coeducational\n| years       = 9\u201313\n| coordinates = {{Coord|37|47|34|S|175|19|34|E|type:edu_region:NZ-WKO|display=inline,title}}\n| established = 1972\n| address     = 132 Masters Avenue<br />Silverdale<br />Hamilton 3216<br />New Zealand\n| principal   = Kelvin Whiting\n| roll        = {{NZ school roll data|138|y||y}}\n| decile      = 7<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.minedu.govt.nz/~/media/MinEdu/Files/EducationSectors/PrimarySecondary/SchoolOpsResourcing/OperationalFundingDeciles/DecileChanges_20142015.xls |title= Decile Change 2014 to 2015 for State & State Integrated Schools |publisher= Ministry of Education |accessdate= 12 February 2015}}</ref>\n| MOE         = 138\n| homepage    = {{URL|hillcrest-high.school.nz/}}\n}}\n\n'''Hillcrest High School''' is a state coeducational secondary school located in south-eastern [[Hamilton, New Zealand|Hamilton]], New Zealand. The school is named after the suburb of [[Hillcrest, Waikato|Hillcrest]] for which it serves, although the school itself is actually located in [[Silverdale, Waikato|Silverdale]]. Opened in 1972,<ref name=\"2new\">{{cite news |url= http://www.stuff.co.nz/waikato-times/news/8402847/Two-new-schools-for-Hamilton |title= Two new schools for Hamilton |publisher= Waikato Times (via Stuff.co.nz) |first= Jonathan |last= Carson |date= 9 March 2013 |accessdate= 23 June 2013}}</ref> the school has a roll of over 1800 students as of 2020. making it the second-largest school in Hamilton following Hamilton Girls High School.<ref name=\"NZ_school_roll_data\" />\n\n==History==\nHillcrest High School is the youngest of the ten state and state-integrated secondary schools in Hamilton, opening for instruction for the first time in January 1972, although it plans to be superseded by a new secondary school at [[Rototuna]] in about 2016.<ref name=\"2new\" /> Like many New Zealand state secondary schools built in the 1970s, Hillcrest was built to the [[New Zealand standard school buildings#S68|S68 standard design]]. The school has three full-sized S68 blocks (B, C, and D blocks) and one half-sized S68 block (western half of E block \u2013 the eastern half is a later addition).\n\n==Enrolment==\nAt the April 2013 Education Review Office (ERO) review of the school, Hillcrest High School had 1630 students, including 35 [[international student]]s. The school roll's gender composition was 47% male and 53% female, and its ethnic composition was 52% [[New Zealand European]] (P\u0101keh\u0101), 20.5% Asian, 14% [[M\u0101ori people|M\u0101ori]], 7% other European, and 4% [[Pacific Islanders]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.ero.govt.nz/Early-Childhood-School-Reports/School-Reports/Hillcrest-High-School-23-08-2013 |title= Hillcrest High School Education Review |date= 23 June 2013 |publisher= Education Review Office |accessdate= 7 December 2015 }}{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==Curriculum==\nThe school examines students using the New Zealand standard, National Certificate of Educational Achievement (NCEA). Cambridge examinations for Mathematics and English are also available for able Year 12 students.\nA wide variety of subjects can be taken at Hillcrest High, ranging from Visual Art to Mechanics, international languages as well as standard subjects such as English, Mathematics and Science.\n\nHillcrest High is reasonably well known because of its academic success. In 2005, Hillcrest students received a total of 54 scholarships, the sixth highest number of scholarships of any high school in the [[North Island, New Zealand|North Island]]. Seven Hillcrest students received Top Scholar Awards from the [[New Zealand Qualifications Authority]] between 2002\u20135.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hillcrest-high.school.nz/showcase.asp?section=scacademic|title=Recent Academic Achievements|publisher=Hillcrest High School|accessdate=29 January 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081014011810/http://www.hillcrest-high.school.nz/showcase.asp?section=scacademic |archivedate=14 October 2008}}</ref> A student in 2008 scored 99% in the Cambridge English exam, achieving the highest score in the world.<ref>{{Cite news|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5eWgIzb2E?url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/stuff/waikatotimes/4845642a6004.html |archivedate=12 February 2009 |title=Students best in the world |url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/stuff/waikatotimes/4845642a6004.html |work=[[Waikato Times]] |date=12 February 2009 |first=Rebecca |last=Harper |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Extracurricular cultural activities==\nHillcrest High often puts on regular concerts and other cultural events. Below, is a brief list of the regular events:\n\n*'''ILC Concert''', held in August every year, hosted by Assistant Principal, Mrs. Sue Radford.\n*'''International Concert''' is held yearly also, in March. The International Concert is held to recognise the multi-culturalness of Hillcrest High. International cuisine can also be sampled beforehand.\n*'''School productions''' is also a regular, three yearly event. Usually a musical and held at a [[Hamilton, New Zealand|Hamilton]] City theatre. These musicals have included [[Seussical]] (2006), a musical based on Dr.Seuss's works, [[Spamalot]] (2009), a musical based on [[Monty Python and the Holy Grail]]. The most recent musical was The Little Mermaid (2018).\n*There are also drama productions held usually at least once a school term. This will usually include a Shakespeare production, a 6th form production and a 7th form production.\n\n==Student groups and clubs==\nInvolvement in cultural activities is an important part of Hillcrest High School. Annual events include the school production and an International Concert that reflects the multiculturalism of the school. The school has social interest groups, including United Nations Youth, [[Amnesty International]], Students Against Drunk Driving, [[Greenpeace]] and an Eastside Pentecostal Christian Group and a [[Bible Society]] Bible study group. The school also offer clubs to students who share the passion of an activity, including a tramping, surf, skateboarding and chess clubs.\n\n==Motto==\nThere are two commonplace Latin pronunciations: in Ecclesiastical Latin the school motto 'Circumspice' is pronounced chir-koom-spee-cheh,<ref>http://www.ewtn.com/expert/answers/ecclesiastical_latin.htm</ref> in Classical Latin it is pronounced as keer-koom-speek-eh.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.shrinesf.org/latin.htm |title=Archived copy |access-date=14 September 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100303131748/http://www.shrinesf.org/latin.htm |archive-date=3 March 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref> It means 'look around you'.\n\n==Notable people==\n*[[James Baker (New Zealand cricketer)|James Baker]], first-class cricketer{{citation needed|date=April 2016}}\n*[[Laura Langman]], plays for the [[Silver Ferns]], the New Zealand international [[Netball]] team. Graduated from this school in 2003.\n*[[Kimbra (musician)|Kimbra Johnson]], musician based in [[Melbourne]], Australia. Graduated from this school in 2007\n*[[Anjali Thakker]], New Zealand ice and inline hockey player. Graduated from this school in 2010.\n*[[Sonia Waddell]], graduated from this school in 1991. Represented New Zealand in [[rowing (sport)|rowing]] at the [[2000 Summer Olympics|2000]] and [[2004 Summer Olympics]]\n*[[Jesse Mulligan]], TV presenter. Graduated from this school in 1994.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/CU1304/S00524/jesse-mulligan-to-defend-worst-tv-show-ever-made.htm|title=Jesse Mulligan to Defend 'worst TV show ever made' {{!}} Scoop News|website=www.scoop.co.nz|access-date=21 February 2018}}</ref>\n*[[Phum Viphurit]], musician. Graduated in 2013\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://archive.is/20130628031439/http://www.ero.govt.nz/Early-Childhood-School-Reports/School-Reports?profileid=138 Education Review Office (ERO) reports for Hillcrest High School]\n\n{{Schools in Waikato}}\n\n[[Category:Secondary schools in Hamilton, New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1972]]\n[[Category:New Zealand secondary schools of S68 plan construction]]\n[[Category:1972 establishments in New Zealand]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=April 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2018}}\n{{advert|date=April 2013}}\n{{Infobox school\n| name        = Hillcrest High School\n| seal_image  = Hhsbadge.png\n| motto       = Circumspice \n| motto_translation= Look Around You\n| fundingtype = State\n| gender      = Coeducational\n| years       = 9\u201313\n| coordinates = {{Coord|37|47|34|S|175|19|34|E|type:edu_region:NZ-WKO|display=inline,title}}\n| established = 1972\n| address     = 132 Masters Avenue<br />Silverdale<br />Hamilton 3216<br />New Zealand\n| principal   = Kelvin Whiting\n| roll        = {{NZ school roll data|138|y||y}}\n| decile      = 7<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.minedu.govt.nz/~/media/MinEdu/Files/EducationSectors/PrimarySecondary/SchoolOpsResourcing/OperationalFundingDeciles/DecileChanges_20142015.xls |title= Decile Change 2014 to 2015 for State & State Integrated Schools |publisher= Ministry of Education |accessdate= 12 February 2015}}</ref>\n| MOE         = 138\n| homepage    = {{URL|hillcrest-high.school.nz/}}\n}}\n\n'''Hillcrest High School''' is a state coeducational secondary school located in south-eastern [[Hamilton, New Zealand|Hamilton]], New Zealand. The school is named after the suburb of [[Hillcrest, Waikato|Hillcrest]] for which it serves, although the school itself is actually located in [[Silverdale, Waikato|Silverdale]]. Opened in 1972,<ref name=\"2new\">{{cite news |url= http://www.stuff.co.nz/waikato-times/news/8402847/Two-new-schools-for-Hamilton |title= Two new schools for Hamilton |publisher= Waikato Times (via Stuff.co.nz) |first= Jonathan |last= Carson |date= 9 March 2013 |accessdate= 23 June 2013}}</ref> the school has a roll of {{NZ school roll data|138|y|}} students as of {{NZ school roll data|||y}}. making it the second-largest school in Hamilton.<ref name=\"NZ_school_roll_data\" />\n\n==History==\nHillcrest High School is the youngest of the ten state and state-integrated secondary schools in Hamilton, opening for instruction for the first time in January 1972, although it plans to be superseded by a new secondary school at [[Rototuna]] in about 2016.<ref name=\"2new\" /> Like many New Zealand state secondary schools built in the 1970s, Hillcrest was built to the [[New Zealand standard school buildings#S68|S68 standard design]]. The school has three full-sized S68 blocks (B, C, and D blocks) and one half-sized S68 block (western half of E block \u2013 the eastern half is a later addition).\n\n==Enrolment==\nAt the April 2013 Education Review Office (ERO) review of the school, Hillcrest High School had 1630 students, including 35 [[international student]]s. The school roll's gender composition was 47% male and 53% female, and its ethnic composition was 52% [[New Zealand European]] (P\u0101keh\u0101), 20.5% Asian, 14% [[M\u0101ori people|M\u0101ori]], 7% other European, and 4% [[Pacific Islanders]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.ero.govt.nz/Early-Childhood-School-Reports/School-Reports/Hillcrest-High-School-23-08-2013 |title= Hillcrest High School Education Review |date= 23 June 2013 |publisher= Education Review Office |accessdate= 7 December 2015 }}{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==Curriculum==\nThe school examines students using the New Zealand standard, National Certificate of Educational Achievement (NCEA). Cambridge examinations for Mathematics and English are also available for able Year 12 students.\nA wide variety of subjects can be taken at Hillcrest High, ranging from Visual Art to Mechanics, international languages as well as standard subjects such as English, Mathematics and Science.\n\nHillcrest High is reasonably well known because of its academic success. In 2005, Hillcrest students received a total of 54 scholarships, the sixth highest number of scholarships of any high school in the [[North Island, New Zealand|North Island]]. Seven Hillcrest students received Top Scholar Awards from the [[New Zealand Qualifications Authority]] between 2002\u20135.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hillcrest-high.school.nz/showcase.asp?section=scacademic|title=Recent Academic Achievements|publisher=Hillcrest High School|accessdate=29 January 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081014011810/http://www.hillcrest-high.school.nz/showcase.asp?section=scacademic |archivedate=14 October 2008}}</ref> A student in 2008 scored 99% in the Cambridge English exam, achieving the highest score in the world.<ref>{{Cite news|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5eWgIzb2E?url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/stuff/waikatotimes/4845642a6004.html |archivedate=12 February 2009 |title=Students best in the world |url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/stuff/waikatotimes/4845642a6004.html |work=[[Waikato Times]] |date=12 February 2009 |first=Rebecca |last=Harper |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Extracurricular cultural activities==\nHillcrest High often puts on regular concerts and other cultural events. Below, is a brief list of the regular events:\n\n*'''ILC Concert''', held in August every year, hosted by Assistant Principal, Mrs. Sue Radford.\n*'''International Concert''' is held yearly also, in March. The International Concert is held to recognise the multi-culturalness of Hillcrest High. International cuisine can also be sampled beforehand.\n*'''School productions''' is also a regular, three yearly event. Usually a musical and held at a [[Hamilton, New Zealand|Hamilton]] City theatre. These musicals have included [[Seussical]] (2006), a musical based on Dr.Seuss's works, [[Spamalot]] (2009), a musical based on [[Monty Python and the Holy Grail]]. The most recent musical was The Little Mermaid (2018).\n*There are also drama productions held usually at least once a school term. This will usually include a Shakespeare production, a 6th form production and a 7th form production.\n\n==Student groups and clubs==\nInvolvement in cultural activities is an important part of Hillcrest High School. Annual events include the school production and an International Concert that reflects the multiculturalism of the school. The school has social interest groups, including United Nations Youth, [[Amnesty International]], Students Against Drunk Driving, [[Greenpeace]] and an Eastside Pentecostal Christian Group and a [[Bible Society]] Bible study group. The school also offer clubs to students who share the passion of an activity, including a tramping, surf, skateboarding and chess clubs.\n\n==Motto==\nThere are two commonplace Latin pronunciations: in Ecclesiastical Latin the school motto 'Circumspice' is pronounced chir-koom-spee-cheh,<ref>http://www.ewtn.com/expert/answers/ecclesiastical_latin.htm</ref> in Classical Latin it is pronounced as keer-koom-speek-eh.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.shrinesf.org/latin.htm |title=Archived copy |access-date=14 September 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100303131748/http://www.shrinesf.org/latin.htm |archive-date=3 March 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref> It means 'look around you'.\n\n==Notable people==\n*[[James Baker (New Zealand cricketer)|James Baker]], first-class cricketer{{citation needed|date=April 2016}}\n*[[Laura Langman]], plays for the [[Silver Ferns]], the New Zealand international [[Netball]] team. Graduated from this school in 2003.\n*[[Kimbra (musician)|Kimbra Johnson]], musician based in [[Melbourne]], Australia. Graduated from this school in 2007\n*[[Anjali Thakker]], New Zealand ice and inline hockey player. Graduated from this school in 2010.\n*[[Sonia Waddell]], graduated from this school in 1991. Represented New Zealand in [[rowing (sport)|rowing]] at the [[2000 Summer Olympics|2000]] and [[2004 Summer Olympics]]\n*[[Jesse Mulligan]], TV presenter. Graduated from this school in 1994.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/CU1304/S00524/jesse-mulligan-to-defend-worst-tv-show-ever-made.htm|title=Jesse Mulligan to Defend 'worst TV show ever made' {{!}} Scoop News|website=www.scoop.co.nz|access-date=21 February 2018}}</ref>\n*[[Phum Viphurit]], musician. Graduated in 2013\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://archive.is/20130628031439/http://www.ero.govt.nz/Early-Childhood-School-Reports/School-Reports?profileid=138 Education Review Office (ERO) reports for Hillcrest High School]\n\n{{Schools in Waikato}}\n\n[[Category:Secondary schools in Hamilton, New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1972]]\n[[Category:New Zealand secondary schools of S68 plan construction]]\n[[Category:1972 establishments in New Zealand]]\n", "name_user": "Oliver Arancibia", "label": "safe", "comment": "i updated the amount of students that attend the school", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hillcrest_High_School,_Hamilton"}
{"title_page": "Park Sun-ho", "text_new": "{{For|South Korean track cyclist|Park Seon-ho}}\n{{Korean name|Park}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name            = Park Sun-ho\n| image           = 190102 \ubc15\uc120\ud638 MBN '\ucd5c\uace0\uc758 \uce58\ud0a8' \uc81c\uc791\ubc1c\ud45c\ud68c \uc9c1\ucea0 02.png\n| image_size      =\n| birth_name      =\n| birth_date      = {{Birth date and age|1993|5|9}}\n| birth_place     = [[Seoul]], South Korea\n| occupation      = Actor, model, singer\n| years_active    =\n| education       =\n| agent           = [[SidusHQ]]\n| module          = {{Infobox Korean name|child=yes|color=transparent|\n| hangul          = {{linktext|\ubc15|\uc120\ud638}}\n| hanja           = {{linktext|\u6734|\u5ba3|\u6d69}}\n| rr              = Bak Seon-ho\n| mr              = Pak S\u014fnho\n}}}}\n\n'''Park Sun-ho''' (born May 9, 1993) is a South Korean actor, singer, and model. Park made his acting debut in the MBC [[Korean drama|television series]] ''[[Golden Rainbow (TV series)|Golden Rainbow]]'' in 2014. Simiarly, he debuted as a singer in 2014 with the song \"After Love\" (Ballad Ver.) for the 2014 television series ''Love Cells''.<ref>https://music.bugs.co.kr/album/20038690</ref>\n\nMost recently, Park is known for being a contestant on the Mnet boy group survival program ''[[Produce X 101]]'' (2019) and as Lee Gwangchul in the OCN television series ''[[Rugal (TV series)|Rugal]]'' (2020).\n\n\n==Career==\n===2008 - 2014: Early Music Aspirations===\nPark initially planned wanted to debut as a [[Korean idol]], and successfully passed the auditions at [[Starship Entertainment]] in 2008 to become a trainee. He trained at agency for six years before leaving the company in early 2014 after having failed to debut with both [[Boyfriend (band)|Boyfriend]] in 2011 and what would later become [[Monsta X]] in 2014. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://entertain.naver.com/read?oid=144&aid=0000609136|script-title=ko:\u201c\ub0b4\uac8c\ub294 \uc544\ud508 \ub3d9\uc0dd\u201d\u2026\u2018\ud504\ub85c\ub4c0\uc2a4X101\u2019 \uc18c\uc720, \ubc15\uc120\ud638 \ub4f1\uc7a5\uc5d0 \ub208\ubb3c [\uac04\ubc24TV] |date=4 May 2019|website=Sports Kyunghyang|language=ko}}</ref> During his time at Starship, he appeared in both Sistar's \"Give It to Me\" and Sistar19's \"Ma Boy\" music videos.\n\n===2014 - 2019: Career Change to Acting & Debut as a Singer===\nAfter leaving Starship, Park decided to pursue an acting career. After signing with SidusHQ in mid 2014, Park made his acting debut in the drama ''[[Golden Rainbow (TV series)|Golden Rainbow]]'', playing the role of Kim Young-won /\nMichinski Forever in the 34th episode of the series.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.topstarnews.net/news/articleView.html?idxno=626442|script-title=ko: \ubc15\uc120\ud638, \u2018\ud504\ub85c\ub4c0\uc2a4101 \uc2dc\uc98c4\u2019 \ucd9c\uc5f0 \uc804 SNS \uac8c\uc2dc\ubb3c \ubcf4\ub2c8\u2026\u201c\ud589\ubcf5\ud569\uc2dc\ub2e4\u201d  |date=18 May 2019|website=topstarnewshd|language=ko}}</ref>\n\nA rising new actor, he was since been cast as one of the lead in ''Love Cells'' (2014), ''Start Again'' (2016) and ''[[I'm Sorry, But I Love You]]'' (2016).<ref>{{cite web|title=[My Name] \ubc15\uc120\ud638 (1)|url=http://tenasia.hankyung.com/archives/726697|work=10Asia|accessdate=2017-04-20|date=9 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Kim Yoo-jeong, Park Sun-ho, Park Hyeon-woo-I, Choi Young-min donate talent for stray dogs|url=http://www.hancinema.net/kim-yoo-jeong-park-sun-ho-park-hyeon-woo-i-choi-young-min-donate-talent-for-stray-dogs-88933.html|website=[[Hancinema]]|accessdate=2017-04-20|date=27 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nPark also made his debut as a singer in 2014 with the song \"After Love\" (Ballad Ver.), which was included in the second soundtrack album for ''Love Cells''.<ref>https://music.bugs.co.kr/album/20038690</ref>\n\n===2019 - present: ''Produce X 101'' & Growing Popularity===\nPark released a second song in February 2019, \"Still (\uaca8\uc6b8\uc744 \uac77\ub2e4)\", and also contributed to the song's lyrics and music.<ref>https://music.bugs.co.kr/track/31461871?wl_ref=list_tr_08_abM</ref>\n\nIn March 2019, Park was revealed to be a trainee for ''Produce X 101'', the 2019 boy group survival reality show on [[Mnet]].<ref>https://www.instagram.com/p/BvdEjPvAal0/</ref> During the show's first episode on May 3, 2019, he revealed that he joined the show admist a growing succesful acting career due to wanting to try pursuing an idol career once more.  He recieved a 'B' rank in the evaluations,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://entertain.naver.com/read?oid=144&aid=0000609136|script-title=ko:\u201c\ub0b4\uac8c\ub294 \uc544\ud508 \ub3d9\uc0dd\u201d\u2026\u2018\ud504\ub85c\ub4c0\uc2a4X101\u2019 \uc18c\uc720, \ubc15\uc120\ud638 \ub4f1\uc7a5\uc5d0 \ub208\ubb3c [\uac04\ubc24TV] |date=4 May 2019|website=Sports Kyunghyang|language=ko}}</ref> and would go on to finish in 25th place with 814,160+ votes.\n\nUpon conclusion of his time on ''Produce X 101'', Park planned to hold a fanmeeting, titled \"Stand By Me\" on August 17, 2019. However, the fanmeeting would be postponed for undisclosed reasons.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://entertain.naver.com/read?oid=477&aid=0000200585|script-title=ko: \ubc15\uc120\ud638 \uccab \ud32c\ubbf8\ud305 \uc5f0\uae30 \"\ub2a6\uc5b4\uc9c0\ub354\ub77c\ub3c4 \uaf2d \uc9c0\ud0a4\uaca0\ub2e4\"[\uc804\ubb38]|date=9 August 2019|website=SPOTV News|language=ko}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2019, Park was cast in the role of Lee Gwangchul for the OCN drama ''[[Rugal (TV series)|Rugal]]'', which is being distributed internationally by Netflix.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://entertain.naver.com/read?oid=382&aid=0000771209|script-title=ko: \ubc15\uc120\ud638 \u2018\ub8e8\uac08\u2019 \ucd9c\uc5f0\ud655\uc815\u2026 \ub370\ubdd4 \uc774\ud6c4 \uccab \uc7a5\ub974\ubb3c \ub3c4\uc804 [\uacf5\uc2dd\uc785\uc7a5] |date=24 October 2019|website=SportsDonga|language=ko}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://kof.inven.co.kr/dataninfo/fighter/?code=21200|title=\ud0b9 \uc624\ube0c \ud30c\uc774\ud130 \uc62c\uc2a4\ud0c0 \uc778\ubca4 - AS \ubc14\ub2e5\uc744 \ubaa8\ub974\ub294 \uc695\ub9dd\uc758 \ub8e8\uac08|website=kof.inven.co.kr|language=ko|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> The show began airing on March 28, 2020.\n\n== Filmography ==\n\n=== Television series ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Network\n! Ref.\n|-\n| 2014 || ''[[Golden Rainbow (TV series)|Golden Rainbow]]'' || Kim Young-won / <br /> Michinski Forever || [[Munhwa Broadcasting Corporation|MBC]]\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://entertain.naver.com/read?oid=109&aid=0002730499|script-title=ko:\uc2e0\uc608 \ubc15\uc120\ud638\u00b7\ud5ec\ub85c\ube44\ub108\uc2a4 \uc720\uc544\ub77c, \u2018\ud669\uae08\ubb34\uc9c0\uac1c\u2019 \ud569\ub958|date=8 March 2014|website=Osen|language=ko}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2014 || ''Love Cells'' || Ma Dae-choong || [[Naver]] <br /> TV Cast\n| <ref>{{cite web|title=Jang Hyeok, Kim Woo-bin and Kim Yoo-jeong in ''Love Cells''|url=http://www.hancinema.net/jang-hyeok-kim-woo-bin-and-kim-yoo-jeong-in-love-cells-73419.html|website=[[Hancinema]]|accessdate=2017-04-20|date=16 September 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=2|2015 || ''[[Shine or Go Crazy]]'' || Wang Wi || MBC\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://entertain.naver.com/read?oid=382&aid=0000305725|script-title=ko:\ubc15\uc120\ud638, \u2018\ube5b\ub098\uac70\ub098 \ubbf8\uce58\uac70\ub098\u2019 \ud569\ub958\u2026 \uc7a5\ud601\uacfc \ub450 \ubc88\uc9f8 \uc778\uc5f0|date=12 January 2015|website=Sports Donga|language=ko}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''Rude Miss Young-ae - Season 14'' || Park Sun-ho || [[TVN (South Korea)|tvN]]\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://entertain.naver.com/read?oid=382&aid=0000368582|script-title=ko:\u2018\ub9c9\uc601\uc560\u2019, \uc2dc\uc98c14\ub85c \ub3cc\uc544\uc654\ub2e4\u2026 \ub300\ubcf8\ub9ac\ub529 \ud604\uc7a5 \uacf5\uac1c|date=17 June 2015|website=Sports Donga|language=ko}}</ref>\n|-\n|rowspan=2|2016 || ''Start Again'' || Kang Ji-wook || MBC\n|<ref>{{cite web|title=''Let's Make a New Start'' leading actors Park Min-ji, Woori, Kim Jeong-hoon and Park Sun-ho share snapshot|url=http://www.hancinema.net/-let-s-make-a-new-start-leading-actors-park-min-ji-woori-kim-jeong-hoon-and-park-sun-ho-share-snapshot-94963.html|website=[[Hancinema]]|accessdate=2017-04-20|date=27 May 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[I'm Sorry, But I Love You]]'' || Kang Nam-goo || [[Seoul Broadcasting System|SBS]]\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://entertain.naver.com/read?oid=112&aid=0002871225|title=\ubc15\uc120\ud638X\uae40\ubbfc\uc11c, SBS \uc77c\uc77c\uadf9 '\uc544\uc784\uc3d8\ub9ac \uac15\ub0a8\uad6c' \uc8fc\uc778\uacf5|date=1 December 2016|website=TV Report|language=ko}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2017 || [[Hospital Ship (TV series)|''Hospital Ship'']] || Kim Jae-hwan || MBC\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://entertain.naver.com/read?oid=421&aid=0002849143|script-title=ko:\ubc15\uc120\ud638, '\ubcd1\uc6d0\uc120' \ud569\ub958\u2026\ud558\uc9c0\uc6d0 \ud6c4\ubc30 \uc758\uc0ac \ubcc0\uc2e0 [\uacf5\uc2dd]|date=20 July 2017|website=News1|language=ko}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2018 || ''[[A Poem a Day]]'' || Han Joo-yong || tvN\n| <ref>{{cite news|author=Shin, So-won|url=http://entertain.naver.com/read?oid=117&aid=0003000310|script-title=ko:[\ub2e8\ub3c5] \"\uc0e4\ubc29\uc0e4\ubc29 \uc120\ud638\uc528\" \ubc15\uc120\ud638, '\uc2dc\ub97c \uc78a\uc740 \uadf8\ub300\uc5d0\uac8c' \ucd9c\uc5f0\ud655\uc815|website=Naver|publisher=My Daily|language=ko|date=2018-01-15|accessdate=2018-04-09}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2018 || ''Love Your Glow'' || Kim Soo || Naver TVCast\n| <ref>{{cite news|author=Jung, An-jee|url=https://news.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2018/11/08/2018110801020.html|script-title=ko:[\ub2e8\ub3c5] \ubc15\uc120\ud638, \uc6f9\ub4dc '\ud53c\uc5b4\ub098' \ub0a8\uc8fc \ucd9c\uc5f0 \ud655\uc815\u2026\ud328\uc158\uae30\uc5c5 CEO \ubcc0\uc2e0 |website=Chosun.com|publisher=Sports Chosun|language=ko|date=2018-11-08|accessdate=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2019 || ''[[Best Chicken]]'' || Park Choi-go || [[Maeil Broadcasting Network|MBN]] and Dramax